column5:
Cenk, I wish TYT was more responsible with its language. The word paedophile is inaccurately used again and again here, and this can have dangerous consequences for people who have never, and would never do anything to hurt anyone else. Paedophile is a word that describes a person who is sexually attracted to children, ie to pre-pubescents, typically 11-12 and younger. The person here is 14, and past puberty. People who are past puberty are sexually mature and their bodies send out signals that they are ready for sex, which are picked up by members of the opposite sex. OF course, in the modern era, we rightly recognise the category of teenagers, and we understand that teenagers' brains are not fully developed, and that there is a power imbalance between a mature adult and a confused teenager, so we have enacted age of consent laws. But there are still several important distinctions to be made here. The word Hebephile exists to describe people who have attraction to teenagers, ie to people who are sexually developed, but recognised as still immature mentally and emotionally. Paedophile is an inaccurate word, and one that only serves to get people angry, too often at people who have never done anything wrong, and lived very unfortunate lives, cursed with an attraction to children that they did not choose, and which they do not want to have, and who are terrified that they will be found out and have their lives ruined, even though they would never harm anyone.
It is also interesting to note how the category of child has expanded in recent years. Prior to fairly recently, the term teenager did not even exist. Children were recognised as human beings in the age range from baby to about 11-12, around the time puberty struck. At this time they were no longer considered children. Some cultures considered them as fully grown adults, while others did not confer adult status until around 18-21, the Romans being an example of this, but in all these cultures people began to be treated very much like adults when puberty struck. They were expected to put away their toys and begin doing adult things. Then, in the 20th century, a more concrete category was created, that of teenager, and a whole culture rose around this, including the expectation that they would remain in school beyond the age of 11 or 12, and that adulthood really did not begin until the late teens. In America the drinking age suggests that this is even later. 
What has been happening in the last few years, however, is something that is unique to human societies, namely the expansion of childhood into the teenage years. We rarely hear of people aged 13-17 as teenagers anymore, as they are instead called children. It is common parlance in schools and all educational settings, and more and more common in the media. This is a strange development, one that seems to me to be explained by the culture of fear and paranoia that we have developed, of coddling children beyond reason, of following them around everywhere, of imagining rapists and pedos hiding in the bushes. We all hear stories from our elders about how in their day kids would be outside playing until it got dark, and kids were left to figure a lot out for themselves. It is this change in culture that has inevitably led to this strange expansion of childhood, where we get to the point that a 14 year old is treated as if she were a 4 year old, and described by media members as a little girl, when in fact for most of human history she would have been treated as an adult. 
Of course none of this diminishes what Roy Moore seems to have done, the main two points being that he has done something against another's will, and that that person was below the age of consent. This is defined as sexual assault, not as paedophilia. Again, paedophilia is the ATTRACTION towards PRE-PUBESCENT children, not teenagers, and not any actual act of harm. The act of harm is defined as sexual assault, regardless of age. These may seem meaningless distinctions to many people, but they are important. There are a lot of people out there who have this attraction to children, and instead of demonising these potentially millions of people and filling them with paranoia and fear that if they are discovered they will be lynched, we should instead be working to open up our society's understanding, so that they can get help, therapy, counselling, support, and to ensure that they will never do anything to actual children. If a person lives a life of fear and feels they have nothing left to lose, then they are more likely to commit a harmful act against another. This is important, and if we actually do care about children (it seems that more often we care about demonising, beating the other political side, virtue signalling, and creating an atmosphere of panic) then we should take these matters seriously and worry about the actual meanings of words. 
And yes, for those of you who are intellectually incapable of reading anything with nuance and detachment about emotional subjects, feel free to call me a raging pedo and whatever else you like. If it makes you feel better than I am happy to help out.

It's amazing with what accuracy I was able to predict this reaction. For some people they are put off by the fact that there are lots of words. For others the words are too complicated. For others the subject matter demands that unless one sticks to the script one is automatically a pedophile rapist. I have not said a single thing that is controversial or not true, and yet not single person commenting here can do anything other than react with anger. 
Let me clarify again my positions, so that people will stop (unlikely) strawmanning me.
Pedophile does not mean what most people think it means. A pedophile describes a person who is sexually ATTRACTED to pre-pubescent children, not teenagers, and it merely describes ATTRACTION, not actual abuse or assault. That is pederasty, or just plain assault. A person who assaults a child is not necessarily attracted to them, so not necessarily a pedophile. 

I did not say that 14 year olds are fully developed. I said that they are sexually developed, ie capable of having children. This is evidenced by the fact that in many cultures this is a 'normal' age to get married and have children.

I am not defending Roy Moore. He assaulted a young woman against her will, and broke age of consent laws.
 
I am not defending the idea of marrying or having sex with teenagers. I believe, as I made clear, that age of consent laws are in place for a reason, because teenagers are generally not emotionally or intellectually mature enough and can be taken advantage of by adults. 

The meaning of words matters. Nuance matters. 

I am very puzzled by the 'moral' person here who hopes that my daughter will be molested. 

The reason I think these distinctions are important is because there are a lot, and I mean a LOT of people who are sexually atracted to children. Estimates are around 1%, and I suspect it is higher. That is 3 million people is the US alone. If we want to keep our children safe from harm we are far better off creating an environment where the unlucky people that are born with an attraction to children can find therapy and couselling , rather than live lives of fear and worry of being found out and killed. Imagine if your son was born this way, and lived a life of terror. What would be better, helping him to control his urges and lead a normal life, or harrassing him, attacking him, and leaving him with nothing to lose? Which one of these options seems more likely to protect children? And does it not also make moral sense that we should try to improve the life of the person suffering from the unwanted desires, so that they can also lead a life as free from suffering as possible? 
You people responding here seem to have liberal attitudes. A true Liberal is interested in lessening the suffering of all people. 
If you are not capable of empathy with the most unlucky of individuals, how do you expect them to behave?
